, England","Owby, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cailly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghailligh</b> ‘son of <i>Raghailleach</i>’. Compare   Crawley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Crawley","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places called Crawley, for example in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Sussex, and Oxfordshire, named with Old English <i>crāwe</i> ‘crow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare   Crowley  .","Irish (Louth): in Ireland, this is generally the English name in 1 above, but it may also have been adopted for <b>McCrawley</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Raghallaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Raghallach</i>’, also Anglicized as <b>Magreely</b>."]},{"name":"Crilley","meanings":["Irish (Derry): variant of   Crilly  ."]},{"name":"Kriley","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Irish   Crilly  ."]},{"name":"Grilley","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of Irish   Crilly  ."]}]},{"name":"or","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Jewish (Israeli): from Hebrew <i>or</i> ‘light’, a Hebraicized form of various original Ashkenazic surnames.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 柯, see   Ke   1.","Chinese: Hokkien form of the surname 胡, see   Hu   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Ke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Heng, Yong, Bin, Song, Yan, Zhi, Cheng, Chih-Ming, Chun-Yen, Fan, Fong, Gang.  Vietnamese Lan, Hai, Hoa, Le Van, Mui, Tuy.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 柯, meaning ‘bough, stalk’ in Chinese: (i) from the first element of the personal name Ke Lu (柯盧), personal name of a prince of the state of Wu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the first element of the placename Ke Ze (柯澤), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to an official in the state of Qi during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) traced back to the Qiang ethnic group in ancient western China and the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) adopted as a surname by the Ke Ba (柯拔) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: variant of   Ge  ."]}]},{"name":"Caley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of the places called Cailly in Eure and Seine-Maritime, France, derived from a Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Callius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>.","English: variant of   Callow   or of <b>Cayley</b>, the latter a habitational name from a minor place called Caley in the parish of Winwick, Lancashire, named with Old English <i>cā</i> ‘jackdaw’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Manx: shortened form of Gaelic <i>Mac Caollaidhe</i> ‘son of <i>Caolladhe</i>’. The personal name is from Gaelic <i>caol</i> ‘slender’."],"variants":[{"name":"Callow","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Callow, including one in Herefordshire which is named with Old English <i>calu</i> ‘bare’ in the sense ‘bare hill’, Callow near Hathersage and Callow near Wirksworth, both in Derbyshire, which are named with Old English <i>cald</i> ‘cold’ + <i>hlāw</i> ‘hill’, and Calow near Chesterfield, also in Derbyshire, which is named with Old English <i>calu</i> ‘bare’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook of land’.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>calwe</i>, <i>calewe</i> (Old English <i>calu</i>, weak accusative and dative case form <i>calewan</i>) ‘bald’.","Manx: shortened Anglicized form of Manx <i>Mac Allow</i> ‘son of Allow’, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Amhlaoibh</i>. The personal name is a borrowing of Old Norse <i>Óláfr</i>."]},{"name":"Calley","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Caley  .","English: variant of the Lancashire name <b>Cayley</b> (see   Caley   2).","Manx: cognate of Scottish Gaelic   Macaulay  , Irish   McAuley  . See also   Cawley   and   Callow  ."]},{"name":"Kailey","meanings":["Manx: variant of   Caley  .","English: variant of <b>Cayley</b>, a habitational name from Cayley in Winwick, Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Cailly or Caley was born in 1315, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William De Cailly, was 11312 and his mother, Catherine, was 33. He married Maud De Pateshull about 1343, in Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. In 1336, at the age of 21, his occupation is listed as sheriff of suffolk. He died in 1395, at the age of 80, and was buried in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1315–1395":"1315–1395","1323–1359":"1323–1359","1344–1380":"1344–1380","1350–1450":"1350–1450","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1283–Female":"1283–Surnud","August 23, 1330":"23. august 1330","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1350":"1350","1283":"1283","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1270":"1270","1315":"1315","1359":"1359","1336":"1336","1335":"1335","about 1305":"umbes 1305","1323":"1323","1344":"1344","about 1343":"umbes 1343","about 1350":"umbes 1350","Owby Manor, High Norfolk, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Normanton,Yorkshire,England":"Normanton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfol